[[Image:Descamisadostatue.jpg|thumb|right|This is a model of a statue called "El Descamisado." This statue was to be built as memorial to [[Eva Perón]]. It was projected to stand taller than the [[Statue of Liberty]], but Juan Perón was overthrown before the monument was completed.]] 

'''Descamisado''' is a [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word that literally means "without shirt" or "shirtless." The term was originally used as an insult by the elite of [[Argentina]] to describe the followers of [[Juan Perón]], who served as [[president of Argentina]] from 1946 until 1955, and then again briefly from 1973 to 1974. The term was later converted into a term of pride, with Juan Perón and his wife [[Eva Perón]] affectionately referring to their followers as "descamisados." And during his 1945 campaign for president, Juan Perón toured the country on a train that he named "El Descamisado." 

By most accounts, the term has its origins on [[October 17]], [[1945]], when thousands of supporters of Juan Perón gathered in front of the [[Casa Rosada]] to demand Perón's release from prison. While waiting for Perón on this hot day, many men in the crowd removed their shirts -- hence the term "shirtless."

The "descamisados" of [[Peronism]] have occasionally been compared to the [[Sans-culottes]] of the [[French Revolution]]. 

